image.caption:
一昨日は雪の中、文具系友人であるT社長が愛車シエラで来社。いよいよアピオカスタム仕様に着手！道中は楽しい万年筆でいうとぬらぬら感のある時間（意味不明）完成した暁の帰路はきっとグラフィーロな乗り心地ですね（深まる謎）さて先日月曜日は某一般誌の文具特集用に取材を受けたばかりですが、本日はまた別の雑誌の寄稿依頼締め切りが迫っている中で、多いなと思っていた3000字があっという間に埋まりました。そういえば小学校から高校生まで作文だけは得意で、速度もはやかった事を思い出しました。そんな中毎日記録しているこのトラベラーズノートのマンスリースケジュールダイアリー（長い）短くいえばマス目日記の画像を撮影する必要もあってさらにインスタの更新を最近していなかったので過去の１月分を並べると最初のスタートした2018年の文字が大きかったことに。翌年からは安定の小ささです。文具話題とジムニーでいえば、発売開始したアピオジムニーのマスキングテープは順調なスタートで、今日だけでアピオ店頭にｍｔテープを買いに来てくれたお客様が何組か。うち２人はジムニーに乗ったジムニー女子でした。

image.alt_text: Photo by TRC-Leiden on February 12, 2022.
image.caption:
This is the lid of a small cardboard box that contained an early 19th century Dutch bridal treasure, from #Zeeland (TRC 2014.1060e). 

The lid is covered with ivory-coloured #satin decorated with chiffon flowers and seeds, with embroidered leaves and stems in #chenille thread and #floss silk. 

Inside were four embroidered ovals, used in a wedding in 1827 and for another wedding in 1903. We think the ovals were used for wedding rings, as one oval was embroidered with the word 'bruid' (Dutch for bride), and the other with 'bruidegom' (bridegroom).

image.alt_text: Photo shared by 𝐒𝐚𝐫𝐚 on February 02, 2022 tagging @maggie_stiefvater. May be an image of one or more people and people standing.
image.caption:
"Wanting to live, but accepting death to save others: that was courage. That was to be Gansey's greatness."

💌 I'm still thinking about it.
The Gangsey bunch left me something that can hardly be described frankly. It was summer when I first ran over the pages of this amazing book series. It was very warm, the sun warming me with its rays to my skin and the air smelled unexpected. I was sitting in a hammock then, overlooking the valley, deep forests and vast meadows. I fell in love right on the first pages. I was absolutely enchanted by every character I read about and I was able to fit into each of the main characters. I fell in love with them. When I read the second book The Dream Thieves, I was able to completely identify my thoughts with Ronan. But over time, I've found that I have dangerously much in common with Adam. And suddenly I had a lot in common with Gansey. In the end, I saw myself in different situations in different characters and it is a sign of a good book for me. I love the relationship between Ronan and Adam, my whole heart belongs to them (Gansey and Blue too, but of course Pynch will always have a more special place in my heart).
My heart belongs to Adam and Ronan. My heart belongs to Blue and Gangsey. My heart belongs to Noah and Henry.
I was part of their party. They were my friends and they took me with them on amazing adventures. They kept me company at a very, very difficult time, and for that I will be forever grateful. I will be forever grateful to you, dear Maggie. 
Thank you with my all heart 🖤

image.alt_text: Photo by Eldridge on February 11, 2022. May be an image of book and text that says 'W THE RAVEN BOYS 25 THE DREAM THIEVES 815 ടള 超 The Child Finder Rene Denfeld డ0గ THE STONE SKY JEMISIN GENDER QUEER MATA KOBABE ALL OF US VILLAINS AMANDA ਪ THE ADVENTUR The Crystal Kingdom'.
image.caption:
The second Friday in February is naturally the perfect time for my January wrap-up 😌 This is my booksta learning experience not to drag out a nine-post series across two months! 
▪︎▪︎▪︎
January's wrap consists of the six physical novels (String Follow, The Raven Boys, The Dream Thieves, The Child Finder, The Stone Sky, and All of Us Villains) and two graphic novels (Gender Queer - a memoir, and TAZ: Crystal Kingdom) pictured, plus one short story (Color & Light), one memoir (I'm Still Here), and three novels (Never Saw Me Coming, Meet Cute Diary, and She Drives Me Crazy) in ebook form. 39% of authors read are from the global majority, and 54% of books included queer/trans representation.

In January, I finished The Broken Earth trilogy, which was such a vast and comprehensive work of art that I'm even more annoyed at how many years it sat on my shelf. I also started The Raven Cycle, which I'll eventually write a post (or seven) about now that I've just finished it. Typically my reading months are not quite so prosperous, either in sheer volume or quality, but this is the one benefit to bedrest: lots of reading time, and time to think about what I'm in the mood for so I can enjoy it more -- except in the case of The Child Finder, which was my single one-star read of the month.
▪︎▪︎▪︎
Would you prefer all your books to be absolute bangers (or at least 4/5 stars), or do you sort of enjoy when some of your books turn into duds?

I find it makes me appreciate the great books more, and because I'm the worst, I enjoy having something to cast the occasional critical eye towards 🤭
▪︎▪︎▪︎

image.alt_text: Photo by Returning To Spirit on January 25, 2022. May be an image of text that says 'numbers were names'.
image.caption:
WARNING: This post contains details some readers may find distressing.

As the T’exelcemc (people of Williams Lake First Nation, BC) share the details today of uncovered graves at the St. Joseph’s Mission Indian Residential School site, we must be reminded that these numbers, they were names. They were children who were loved, cared for & missed deeply by their families & their communities. They were & will always be so much more than a number. The legacy of Residential Schools continues to this day, which is why we continue to do the work to create hope & healing across Canada. To the people of Williams Lake & every community impacted by residential schools, we stand with you. 🧡

For emotional support or assistance please contact The Indian Residential School Survivors Society toll-free 1 (800) 721-0066 or 24hr Crisis Line 1 (866) 925-4419

image.alt_text: Photo by TRC-Leiden on February 05, 2022.
image.caption:
What is this? This is one of 11 ancient Greek loom weights, c. 750-480 BCE, that the TRC has in its collection. 

While a common enough archaeological find, loom weights can tell us a lot. Used on a warp-weighted loom to help keep tension and the threads untangled, different sizes and shapes affect the thread count (the number of threads per centimeter in a weave), thus the fineness of the weaving. 

Changes in size and shape also point to stories of technological innovation and its spread by immigration, trade or war. 

We also learn about gender roles. Greek historian Herodotus was deeply shocked when he learned that in Egypt, it was men who did the weaving. In ancient Greece weaving was deeply associated with women and girls. Learn more on the blog by Shelley Anderson on our website or at our online digital exhibition.

The #TRC depot houses many archaeological textiles, including this warp-faced compound weave (TRC 2000.0009) dated to the 2nd century CE. This silk fragment was discovered by archaeologist Sir Marc Aurel Stein (1862-1943) in the lost city of Niya, a settlement on the ancient Silk Road. 

Read more about these scraps from a lost city in TRC volunteer Shelley Anderson's blog on our website: www.trc-leiden.nl

image.caption:
Fashion designer Manfred Thierry Mugler has died. He first launched his label in 1973 and became famous in the 1980s and 1990s for his creative use of materials like plastic and rubber, and for his iconic use of shoulder pads. Maison Mugler closed in 2003. This feathered butterfly dress is from his 1997 collection Les Insectes.

image.alt_text: Photo by d e j a 💫 on January 15, 2022. May be an image of book and text that says 'STIEFVATER THE RAVEN BOYS STIEFVATER =|5 STIEFVATER THE DREAM THIEVES 15 BLUE LILY, LILY BLUE STIEFVATER |5 THE RAVEN KING STIEFVATER MISTER IMPOSSIBLE STIEFVATER #15 NOWN'.
image.caption:
As much as I love to read, I’m terrible at remembering what happened in a book. Especially when I pick up a new installment after reading the previous books years prior. That’s why I deceived to wait to read books 2 and 3 in The Dreamer Trilogy once the finale releases this fall. I also just prefer to read a series back to back if I’m able to.

I also decided to wait since both The Raven Cycle and The Dreamer Trilogy are very intricate and confusing stories 🌚. I love them so much, and Maggie Stiefvater is definitely one of my favorite writers, ever. But I’ve read The Raven Cycle twice all the way through and still find new things to put together that were apparent to me before. It actually makes for a really fun reading experience, so I’m looking forward to finishing off The Dreamer Trilogy this year and then re-reading it in the future. 

Maggie’s posted art for TRC a few days ago and hinted at it possibly being for The Raven Boys 10th anniversary, so I’m hopeful that I can add a new edition to my collection!

Day 15 of #AlltheBooksJan22 - Series you want to finish this year

image.alt_text: Photo by TRC-Leiden on January 12, 2022.
image.caption:
The TRC has just been given a sample of the "Tears and Lace"  pattern by the  Darquer lace manufacturer. Darquer makes lace for the Elsa Schiaparelli fashion house. The design is based on a photograph from artist Rose-Lynn Fisher's series The Topography of Tears, who studied her own tears under a microscope.

Lace designer Vincent Fasquel  made a digital sketch of the photograph, which was then give a double scalloped edge by Frédéric Rumigny. The design was then worked out by technical draftspeople, and manufactured in 2015 on a Darquer Leavers machine in the #Chantilly technique.

Originally built by @slowtbss after following his progress for years. He did a nice clean job on this bike before he sold it. Currently its getting a little refresh and update thanks to @boomstune_hq and @stpicycles
